01:02:04.910 --> 01:02:07.660
One, my perceptions
of how Harvard

01:02:07.660 --> 01:02:10.510
has changed the most in the
years since I've been here,

01:02:10.510 --> 01:02:13.940
and then also how I've changed
at Harvard in that 20 year

01:02:13.940 --> 01:02:14.440
period.

01:02:14.440 --> 01:02:15.820
And what I realized--

01:02:15.820 --> 01:02:18.070
I think by surprise,
it wasn't something

01:02:18.070 --> 01:02:19.840
I had in the back
of my head even--

01:02:19.840 --> 01:02:23.380
is that both of those
have landed on teaching--

01:02:23.380 --> 01:02:24.970
both Harvard's
approach to teaching,

01:02:24.970 --> 01:02:28.072
and my own thoughts about
how teaching has changed me.

01:02:28.072 --> 01:02:30.280
So I thought I would just
spend a few minutes talking

01:02:30.280 --> 01:02:32.560
about reflections
on both of those.

01:02:32.560 --> 01:02:35.184
And then I've actually gotten
some additional thoughts

01:02:35.184 --> 01:02:37.350
from all the wonderful
comments that came before me.

01:02:37.350 --> 01:02:40.630
So if I have time, I'll
augment, amplify some

01:02:40.630 --> 01:02:42.950
of what you've heard before.

01:02:42.950 --> 01:02:46.060
So you heard Judy say,
right from the beginning,

01:02:46.060 --> 01:02:48.430
that Harvard has changed
quite a bit with regard

01:02:48.430 --> 01:02:53.050
to how it thinks about its
junior faculty members,

01:02:53.050 --> 01:02:54.740
it's non-tenured
faculty members.

01:02:54.740 --> 01:02:56.948
And as you know-- you've
probably already sensed this

01:02:56.948 --> 01:02:59.290
if you've been here in
any capacity before--

01:02:59.290 --> 01:03:01.740
you know that Harvard is
kind of a strange place.

01:03:01.740 --> 01:03:05.380
Like, it likes to do things
in its own particular way,

01:03:05.380 --> 01:03:07.030
even though other
places have kind

01:03:07.030 --> 01:03:10.000
of-- you would have thought--
worked out some of the kinks.

01:03:10.000 --> 01:03:12.700
And one of the ways that
Harvard was strange until fairly

01:03:12.700 --> 01:03:16.300
recently was that almost
all of the tenured faculty

01:03:16.300 --> 01:03:18.410
came from outside of its ranks.

01:03:18.410 --> 01:03:21.730
The non-tenured faculty were
here for some number of years

01:03:21.730 --> 01:03:25.480
before typically moving on
to some other institution.

01:03:25.480 --> 01:03:28.150
And that created a
lot of strangeness,

01:03:28.150 --> 01:03:30.100
and strange dynamics
between faculty,

01:03:30.100 --> 01:03:32.050
and faculty and
students, and lots

01:03:32.050 --> 01:03:34.750
of senior people in
their 60s and 70s,

01:03:34.750 --> 01:03:37.120
and then a bunch of younger
people in their 30s,

01:03:37.120 --> 01:03:39.430
and no one in between.

01:03:39.430 --> 01:03:43.120
But one of the ways that I
think it created strangeness

01:03:43.120 --> 01:03:44.710
was really around teaching.

01:03:44.710 --> 01:03:46.959
Because when you think about
what an institution might

01:03:46.959 --> 01:03:49.354
do in bringing folks from
outside, it's typically,

01:03:49.354 --> 01:03:51.520
you're looking for the best
scholars in that field--

01:03:51.520 --> 01:03:55.840
the best historian of science,
or the best chemical engineer.

01:03:55.840 --> 01:04:00.820
And you may pay less attention
to whether that person's

01:04:00.820 --> 01:04:03.320
a wonderful teacher.

01:04:03.320 --> 01:04:07.090
And so what kind of happened
was that senior faculty--

01:04:07.090 --> 01:04:09.220
and I should also
say, many people

01:04:09.220 --> 01:04:10.959
who were thinking
about coming to Harvard

01:04:10.959 --> 01:04:13.000
might have found it
attractive to come to a place

01:04:13.000 --> 01:04:16.540
where teaching was
emphasized less than

01:04:16.540 --> 01:04:18.070
at their previous institution.

01:04:18.070 --> 01:04:23.170
So much of the teaching devolved
to the younger, junior faculty.

01:04:23.170 --> 01:04:28.510
But there was also a sense that
teachers are sort of born, not

01:04:28.510 --> 01:04:31.660
made, and that there
just wasn't much one

01:04:31.660 --> 01:04:34.000
could do to influence teaching.

01:04:34.000 --> 01:04:36.650
You either had the
knack for it or not.

01:04:36.650 --> 01:04:40.120
And so I think around the time
that the tenure system changed,

01:04:40.120 --> 01:04:42.190
there was also this
realization that we

01:04:42.190 --> 01:04:46.450
could be approaching teaching
the same way that we approach

01:04:46.450 --> 01:04:48.820
many of our mentoring
activities--

01:04:48.820 --> 01:04:51.640
to take individuals who
were new to the classroom,

01:04:51.640 --> 01:04:54.140
or new to the kinds of teaching
they were being asked to do,

01:04:54.140 --> 01:04:57.702
whether it be case methods or
teaching a big lecture course,

01:04:57.702 --> 01:04:59.410
and to try to work
with those individuals

01:04:59.410 --> 01:05:02.720
to improve what it is
they did in the classroom.

01:05:02.720 --> 01:05:05.200
And so over the
last 10 or 15 years,

01:05:05.200 --> 01:05:08.710
Harvard's made what I consider
to be a very sizable investment

01:05:08.710 --> 01:05:12.490
in the infrastructure around
teaching and learning.

01:05:12.490 --> 01:05:17.210
So I'll just mention a couple
of those things that are--

01:05:17.210 --> 01:05:20.500
and as others have said before,
I have a particular lens,

01:05:20.500 --> 01:05:22.490
being an FAS faculty member.

01:05:22.490 --> 01:05:25.190
So not all of this is
relevant to individuals

01:05:25.190 --> 01:05:27.470
in the other schools.

01:05:27.470 --> 01:05:31.240
But I think what is true across
the schools is the renewed

01:05:31.240 --> 01:05:34.220
emphasis on trying
to help individuals--

01:05:34.220 --> 01:05:37.930
especially our new assistant,
associate professors--

01:05:37.930 --> 01:05:40.750
figure out how to be most
effective in the classroom.

01:05:40.750 --> 01:05:45.190
So under the umbrella of
"Harvard likes to do things

01:05:45.190 --> 01:05:47.990
in its own way," what
Harvard has not done,

01:05:47.990 --> 01:05:50.320
at least not in my department,
and I don't think across

01:05:50.320 --> 01:05:52.787
the FAS-- although, it might
be different in your schools--

01:05:52.787 --> 01:05:55.120
is some of the things that
other institutions have done.

01:05:55.120 --> 01:05:59.380
For instance, in the FAS,
there's no FAS-wide policy

01:05:59.380 --> 01:06:03.040
that your teaching is reviewed
by some other faculty member.

01:06:03.040 --> 01:06:06.700
Nobody has literally ever come
into my classroom in the 10

01:06:06.700 --> 01:06:09.130
years I've been teaching
here to try to give me tips.

01:06:09.130 --> 01:06:10.588
That may happen in
your department.

01:06:10.588 --> 01:06:11.362
I hope it does.

01:06:11.362 --> 01:06:12.820
But there's no kind
of expectation.

01:06:12.820 --> 01:06:15.340
I know other places, that's
actually built formally

01:06:15.340 --> 01:06:17.860
into the mentoring process.

01:06:17.860 --> 01:06:19.840
And unlike other
places, there's nobody

01:06:19.840 --> 01:06:22.944
who's ever reviewed a
syllabus I've written.

01:06:22.944 --> 01:06:23.860
I've just been asked--

01:06:23.860 --> 01:06:27.000
I have, for the last 10 years,
been teaching Intro Psych.

01:06:27.000 --> 01:06:30.090
I got a bunch of PowerPoint
slides from the other person

01:06:30.090 --> 01:06:30.779
who teaches it.

01:06:30.779 --> 01:06:32.820
And that's been the extent
to which anybody knows

01:06:32.820 --> 01:06:34.770
what I do inside my classroom.

01:06:34.770 --> 01:06:38.340
So unlike, let's say at Yale,
there's no committee in the FAS

01:06:38.340 --> 01:06:40.950
that reviews course syllabi.

01:06:40.950 --> 01:06:44.487
This is kind of crazy when you
think about it in this way.

01:06:44.487 --> 01:06:46.570
So it's a little bit of
the quirkiness of Harvard.

01:06:46.570 --> 01:06:51.060
But I think it's also in the
spirit of Harvard trying to

01:06:51.060 --> 01:06:56.760
instead not micromanage what
goes on inside your classroom.

01:06:56.760 --> 01:06:59.220
But instead, the FAS
and the university

01:06:59.220 --> 01:07:02.580
have taken the approach of
trying to build infrastructure

01:07:02.580 --> 01:07:09.210
to invest in systemic places
where faculty members can

01:07:09.210 --> 01:07:13.560
improve their teaching and
access resources for improving

01:07:13.560 --> 01:07:14.140
pedagogy.

01:07:14.140 --> 01:07:16.347
So I'll mention a few of those.

01:07:16.347 --> 01:07:18.430
And if you want to follow
up with me at any point,

01:07:18.430 --> 01:07:20.790
I'd be happy to
talk more with you.

01:07:20.790 --> 01:07:23.070
So two things that will
be relevant for, I think,

01:07:23.070 --> 01:07:27.060
everyone in this room is the
Bok Center, which I'm sure most

01:07:27.060 --> 01:07:28.920
of you have heard about by now.

01:07:28.920 --> 01:07:32.430
And the Bok Center
was originally created

01:07:32.430 --> 01:07:35.370
with kind of a limited
mindset to think about,

01:07:35.370 --> 01:07:39.180
how do we improve the
day-to-day, nuts-and-bolts

01:07:39.180 --> 01:07:40.110
aspects of teaching.

01:07:40.110 --> 01:07:43.050
So when I first
encountered the Bok Center

01:07:43.050 --> 01:07:45.090
as a graduate student
in the late '90s,

01:07:45.090 --> 01:07:47.040
lots of what they
did was to say, let's

01:07:47.040 --> 01:07:47.890
talk about what's
going to happen

01:07:47.890 --> 01:07:49.320
on the very first day of class.

01:07:49.320 --> 01:07:50.280
Let's workshop that.

01:07:50.280 --> 01:07:52.200
And that was
incredibly valuable.

01:07:52.200 --> 01:07:55.470
And as I got further
in my career,

01:07:55.470 --> 01:07:58.380
I could access the Bok
Center for other kinds

01:07:58.380 --> 01:07:59.790
of nuts-and-bolts issues--

01:07:59.790 --> 01:08:02.970
I'm having trouble figuring
out how to lecture effectively

01:08:02.970 --> 01:08:03.960
in time management.

01:08:03.960 --> 01:08:07.220
And I had people help work
with me to think through,

01:08:07.220 --> 01:08:09.120
why are your lecturers
not feeling right,

01:08:09.120 --> 01:08:10.860
how can you manage
your time better.

01:08:10.860 --> 01:08:12.990
And you can still
access the Bok Center

01:08:12.990 --> 01:08:15.900
for those kinds of
nuts-and-bolts sorts

01:08:15.900 --> 01:08:18.149
of concerns.

01:08:18.149 --> 01:08:20.309
And I would encourage you
to go over there, even

01:08:20.309 --> 01:08:22.350
in advance of actually
teaching your first class,

01:08:22.350 --> 01:08:25.890
to just talk to them
about tips about what

01:08:25.890 --> 01:08:27.750
to do on the first
day of class, how

01:08:27.750 --> 01:08:31.950
do you manage your time in a
120 minute lecture, et cetera.

01:08:31.950 --> 01:08:35.010
But recently, as you know,
the world has changed.

01:08:35.010 --> 01:08:37.830
And the 120 minute
lecture is not

01:08:37.830 --> 01:08:39.899
the only format we
have available to us,

01:08:39.899 --> 01:08:42.510
nor is the 5 to 10 page paper.

01:08:42.510 --> 01:08:47.975
And so partly spurred on
by innovations and advances

01:08:47.975 --> 01:08:50.196
with digital learning,
the Bok Center,

01:08:50.196 --> 01:08:52.029
and also other parts
of the university which

01:08:52.029 --> 01:08:53.404
I'll talk about
in just a second,

01:08:53.404 --> 01:08:56.010
have also been very
interested in helping

01:08:56.010 --> 01:08:59.189
faculty think through what
they could be doing differently

01:08:59.189 --> 01:09:00.069
in their class.

01:09:00.069 --> 01:09:01.979
So to think through,
sure, I know

01:09:01.979 --> 01:09:04.290
that the five page paper
has been effective for you

01:09:04.290 --> 01:09:05.270
as a learner--

01:09:05.270 --> 01:09:07.680
that the 120 minute
lecture worked for you,

01:09:07.680 --> 01:09:10.052
but given your goals
in this course,

01:09:10.052 --> 01:09:12.510
are there other ways that you
might approach the material--

01:09:12.510 --> 01:09:14.370
everything from the
famed flipped classroom

01:09:14.370 --> 01:09:16.830
that you've heard a lot about
to just thinking through what

01:09:16.830 --> 01:09:18.954
kinds of assignments
you might challenge

01:09:18.954 --> 01:09:21.120
your students with that are
different from the kinds

01:09:21.120 --> 01:09:22.578
of assignments that
you encountered

01:09:22.578 --> 01:09:24.160
when you were an undergraduate.

01:09:24.160 --> 01:09:26.700
So part of that can be accessed
through the Bok Center.

01:09:26.700 --> 01:09:28.200
And again, I encourage
you as you're

01:09:28.200 --> 01:09:31.979
thinking about your courses to
talk to folks over there, who,

01:09:31.979 --> 01:09:34.529
you could disregard all
of their suggestions,

01:09:34.529 --> 01:09:36.870
but will at least help you
think in a different way

01:09:36.870 --> 01:09:38.578
than you're probably
used to about what's

01:09:38.578 --> 01:09:40.979
possible inside your classroom.

01:09:40.979 --> 01:09:43.649
At the same time,
the university has

01:09:43.649 --> 01:09:47.130
other university-wide programs.

01:09:47.130 --> 01:09:50.580
So Peter Bol, who's the
Vice Provost for Advances

01:09:50.580 --> 01:09:53.160
in Learning, runs
a couple of groups

01:09:53.160 --> 01:09:55.720
that have a variety of
different initiatives.

01:09:55.720 --> 01:10:01.080
One is, Peter's group
hosts an entire library

01:10:01.080 --> 01:10:02.700
of digital resources.

01:10:02.700 --> 01:10:04.980
So that could be
everything from,

01:10:04.980 --> 01:10:07.169
hey, I'm teaching this
course, Intro Psych,

01:10:07.169 --> 01:10:09.210
and I really need somebody
to talk to my students

01:10:09.210 --> 01:10:11.100
about the hippocampus--
and I'm just not

01:10:11.100 --> 01:10:13.350
an expert on the hippocampus.

01:10:13.350 --> 01:10:15.670
So it turns out there's
some lecture that somebody

01:10:15.670 --> 01:10:16.740
has filmed, somewhere.

01:10:16.740 --> 01:10:19.290
And maybe it's just a
little five minute blurb,

01:10:19.290 --> 01:10:21.180
and you can insert
that into your course--

01:10:21.180 --> 01:10:23.850
either through
Canvas, the website,

01:10:23.850 --> 01:10:25.080
or show it to your students.

01:10:25.080 --> 01:10:27.060
So that's one kind
of digital resource.

01:10:27.060 --> 01:10:31.500
But everything up to, I can't
get enough TFs for my course,

01:10:31.500 --> 01:10:34.560
is there any other way I could
think about designing sections,

01:10:34.560 --> 01:10:37.935
and all sorts of tools
around rethinking,

01:10:37.935 --> 01:10:39.810
maybe I don't need to
have TFs for my course.

01:10:39.810 --> 01:10:42.480
Maybe we can do this
peer-to-peer, among students.

01:10:42.480 --> 01:10:45.990
Or maybe we can do some kind
of digital platforming of what

01:10:45.990 --> 01:10:47.110
goes on inside sections.

01:10:47.110 --> 01:10:50.320
So that's another area
where resources exist.

01:10:50.320 --> 01:10:54.180
They're not widely
advertised, but I

01:10:54.180 --> 01:10:56.400
know that group is very
eager to have faculty

01:10:56.400 --> 01:11:00.790
from across the schools
access those resources.

01:11:00.790 --> 01:11:04.170
And then finally, I'll mention
HILT, the Hauser Initiative

01:11:04.170 --> 01:11:08.320
in Learning and Teaching,
which provides small, startup,

01:11:08.320 --> 01:11:11.160
what they often call
Spark Grants, for faculty

01:11:11.160 --> 01:11:13.260
who want to try something
new in their course.

01:11:13.260 --> 01:11:15.840
That might be to create
some new resource,

01:11:15.840 --> 01:11:18.480
or to help offset
personnel who will

01:11:18.480 --> 01:11:22.050
help you think very differently
about what it is you're doing.

01:11:22.050 --> 01:11:24.970
There's a couple of other
FAS-specific resources,

01:11:24.970 --> 01:11:26.550
which I won't mention now.

01:11:26.550 --> 01:11:28.330
But if you're
interested in accessing

01:11:28.330 --> 01:11:30.850
some of these
pedagogical resources,

01:11:30.850 --> 01:11:33.280
again, I'm happy to
talk about any of this.

01:11:33.280 --> 01:11:35.350
Feel free to email
me at any point.

01:11:35.350 --> 01:11:39.250
Part of my mission,
role, as faculty director

01:11:39.250 --> 01:11:40.780
of the Program in
General Education,

01:11:40.780 --> 01:11:43.570
is to talk to new faculty
about ideas they have.

01:11:43.570 --> 01:11:45.850
Maybe not right now, as
you start your career here,

01:11:45.850 --> 01:11:47.020
but things that you
might be interested

01:11:47.020 --> 01:11:48.103
in sometime in the future.

01:11:50.620 --> 01:11:52.894
So that's, I think, how
Harvard has changed--

01:11:52.894 --> 01:11:54.310
at least, my
experience of Harvard

01:11:54.310 --> 01:11:55.942
has changed-- since
I've come here.

01:11:55.942 --> 01:11:57.400
And I thought I
would also just say

01:11:57.400 --> 01:12:01.690
a little bit about how
teaching has changed me

01:12:01.690 --> 01:12:05.150
as a scholar and intellectual.

01:12:05.150 --> 01:12:09.310
So maybe some of you have
this intuition as well.

01:12:09.310 --> 01:12:13.120
I felt like from the moment I
took Intro Psych as a freshman,

01:12:13.120 --> 01:12:15.280
through everything I ever
did as a psychologist

01:12:15.280 --> 01:12:19.660
for the next 10 years, was
sort of like this decreasingly

01:12:19.660 --> 01:12:20.720
sized funnel.

01:12:20.720 --> 01:12:22.240
It went from this
really big picture

01:12:22.240 --> 01:12:23.980
of the field and
all the excitement

01:12:23.980 --> 01:12:26.440
around learning the
whole panoply of what's

01:12:26.440 --> 01:12:28.960
out there in psychology to
drilling down to very, very

01:12:28.960 --> 01:12:31.420
specific problems
within the field,

01:12:31.420 --> 01:12:34.240
writing grants and
papers, and becoming

01:12:34.240 --> 01:12:37.330
an expert in something.

01:12:37.330 --> 01:12:40.180
And I realized that the moment
where that really changed,

01:12:40.180 --> 01:12:43.570
where the funnel
started expanding again,

01:12:43.570 --> 01:12:46.580
was the moment that I
started teaching Intro Psych.

01:12:46.580 --> 01:12:48.310
And what that course
has done for me,

01:12:48.310 --> 01:12:52.952
it has really forced me to
start to think about the field

01:12:52.952 --> 01:12:54.910
through a lens that's
much broader than the one

01:12:54.910 --> 01:12:56.826
I get by just talking
to my graduate students,

01:12:56.826 --> 01:12:59.810
or doing the kinds of
scholarly work that I do.

01:12:59.810 --> 01:13:01.240
And so without
that experience, I

01:13:01.240 --> 01:13:06.700
feel like I would be a much more
narrow intellectual, scholar,

01:13:06.700 --> 01:13:10.840
academic than I ever would have
been after that experience.

01:13:10.840 --> 01:13:12.930
And so I think, OK,
that's all well and good.

01:13:12.930 --> 01:13:14.290
We like to be intellectuals.

01:13:14.290 --> 01:13:16.690
But then I thought, just
for selfish reasons,

01:13:16.690 --> 01:13:23.650
I feel like beyond just
my own personal enjoyment

01:13:23.650 --> 01:13:25.960
of that experience, it
has actually affected

01:13:25.960 --> 01:13:28.900
my scholarship in ways that I
could never have anticipated,

01:13:28.900 --> 01:13:30.820
were I not to have the
teaching experience.

01:13:30.820 --> 01:13:32.710
It's helped me
understand how what I do

01:13:32.710 --> 01:13:34.930
fits into a much bigger picture.

01:13:34.930 --> 01:13:37.750
It's often pointed
places out to me

01:13:37.750 --> 01:13:41.050
where there just isn't research
being done, or not as much

01:13:41.050 --> 01:13:43.290
as you'd like, and so
suggested questions

01:13:43.290 --> 01:13:46.630
that I didn't actually
know were there.

01:13:46.630 --> 01:13:49.480
And also, as someone
said, this place

01:13:49.480 --> 01:13:51.550
is full of all sorts of
different kinds of people

01:13:51.550 --> 01:13:53.299
from all sorts of
different walks of life.

01:13:53.299 --> 01:13:56.140
And probably the most diverse
group on the entire campus

01:13:56.140 --> 01:13:57.697
is our undergraduates.

01:13:57.697 --> 01:14:00.030
And as you'll see as you're--
for those of you who are--

01:14:00.030 --> 01:14:02.200
especially teaching
in the FAS, it's

01:14:02.200 --> 01:14:05.800
an enormous source both
of personal joy, but also

01:14:05.800 --> 01:14:08.230
intellectual
excitement to engage

01:14:08.230 --> 01:14:11.600
in this way with students.

01:14:11.600 --> 01:14:14.230
So that's just my own
personal reflection

01:14:14.230 --> 01:14:18.262
on what it means to teach here.

01:14:18.262 --> 01:14:19.720
Could I take a
couple more minutes?

01:14:19.720 --> 01:14:20.220
OK.

01:14:23.087 --> 01:14:24.670
Occasionally, you'll
hear someone talk

01:14:24.670 --> 01:14:27.457
about how they've
gotten teaching relief,

01:14:27.457 --> 01:14:29.290
as if they put teaching
in the same category

01:14:29.290 --> 01:14:32.620
as dental pain and
hemorrhoids or something.

01:14:32.620 --> 01:14:34.180
It never feels like that to me.

01:14:34.180 --> 01:14:36.220
I have always thought,
yes, sometimes I'm

01:14:36.220 --> 01:14:38.180
exhausted by the
demands of teaching,

01:14:38.180 --> 01:14:41.590
but in general, I have gotten
more out of it than I think,

01:14:41.590 --> 01:14:44.580
probably, my students
have gotten out of me.

01:14:44.580 --> 01:14:46.330
I wanted to say a
couple other things that

01:14:46.330 --> 01:14:48.400
were just spurred on
by various comments,

01:14:48.400 --> 01:14:50.990
mostly to amplify them.

01:14:50.990 --> 01:14:54.280
And Judy mentioned President
Faust's One Harvard Initiative,

01:14:54.280 --> 01:14:55.640
which is fantastic.

01:14:55.640 --> 01:15:00.520
But despite the attempt
to bring us all on board,

01:15:00.520 --> 01:15:02.530
I want to remind everyone
here that there is

01:15:02.530 --> 01:15:04.180
no such thing as one Harvard.

01:15:04.180 --> 01:15:07.595
That is, Harvard
is not one thing.

01:15:07.595 --> 01:15:08.470
I'm reminded of how--

01:15:08.470 --> 01:15:09.880
I grew up in New York City.

01:15:09.880 --> 01:15:13.477
And most people think about
New York City in a particular--

01:15:13.477 --> 01:15:14.310
like a little slice.

01:15:14.310 --> 01:15:18.370
They think of Times Square
and seeing Broadway plays.

01:15:18.370 --> 01:15:19.954
And maybe getting
on a bus and seeing

01:15:19.954 --> 01:15:22.120
Grant's tomb and the Statue
of Liberty or something.

01:15:22.120 --> 01:15:25.320
But that's some very, very
tiny slice of New York City.

01:15:25.320 --> 01:15:27.400
There's 7 million
other experiences

01:15:27.400 --> 01:15:29.800
of New York City besides
that, most of which

01:15:29.800 --> 01:15:31.120
have nothing to do with that.

01:15:31.120 --> 01:15:34.990
And Harvard lends itself to the
same sorts of misconceptions.

01:15:34.990 --> 01:15:37.060
Even now, when I think
about what Harvard

01:15:37.060 --> 01:15:41.920
is, I think of some guy with
a big gray beard who speaks

01:15:41.920 --> 01:15:47.470
in iambic pentameter at faculty
meetings, and starts off

01:15:47.470 --> 01:15:50.040
by saying, in my 47
years here at Harvard,

01:15:50.040 --> 01:15:52.600
I have never been so
angry, at whatever

01:15:52.600 --> 01:15:54.580
it is that they're angry about.

01:15:54.580 --> 01:15:57.090
And that is definitely
part of Harvard.

01:15:57.090 --> 01:16:00.790
There is a Harvard
that does that.

01:16:00.790 --> 01:16:03.580
And there's the Harvard of
Nobel laureates, and New Yorker

01:16:03.580 --> 01:16:07.450
contributors, and
National Academy members,

01:16:07.450 --> 01:16:10.420
and all of those things
that make Harvard wonderful.

01:16:10.420 --> 01:16:12.790
And then there's the
Harvard of the people

01:16:12.790 --> 01:16:15.490
in this room, the
people who are coming

01:16:15.490 --> 01:16:16.900
to this place for
the first time,

01:16:16.900 --> 01:16:19.316
often from different places
with completely different ways

01:16:19.316 --> 01:16:21.670
of doing things, with a
completely different lens

01:16:21.670 --> 01:16:23.200
on what's possible.

01:16:23.200 --> 01:16:26.080
And there's the Harvard of
our graduate students, who

01:16:26.080 --> 01:16:29.050
are eager to engage
for the first time

01:16:29.050 --> 01:16:30.970
in the same serious
way that we do,

01:16:30.970 --> 01:16:33.910
with the kinds of work that
animates us and keeps us up

01:16:33.910 --> 01:16:34.540
at night.

01:16:34.540 --> 01:16:35.950
And there are the
undergraduates,

01:16:35.950 --> 01:16:41.316
as I mentioned before, who are
spectacular and open vessels

01:16:41.316 --> 01:16:43.690
for the kinds of things that
we want to teach them about.

01:16:43.690 --> 01:16:46.270
There are the administrators,
who make this place run.

01:16:46.270 --> 01:16:51.100
And each of those groups
is contributing to Harvard

01:16:51.100 --> 01:16:52.580
in its own particular way.

01:16:52.580 --> 01:16:55.780
And so one of the things that
I have only recently begun

01:16:55.780 --> 01:16:59.590
to realize is that there are
many paths through this place.

01:16:59.590 --> 01:17:02.440
If you may want to be
that person in 47 years

01:17:02.440 --> 01:17:05.350
time who gets up and throws a
shoe at the faculty meeting,

01:17:05.350 --> 01:17:08.140
and that's wonderful, but
you may want your Harvard

01:17:08.140 --> 01:17:11.260
to be one of political
activism, as we've

01:17:11.260 --> 01:17:14.080
begun to see many of our
faculty are interested in.

01:17:14.080 --> 01:17:17.260
Or you may want your
Harvard to be an investment

01:17:17.260 --> 01:17:20.120
in undergraduates.

01:17:20.120 --> 01:17:22.630
That's your particular slice
of what it means to be a here.

01:17:22.630 --> 01:17:25.046
So I would just encourage
you to remind yourself

01:17:25.046 --> 01:17:26.920
that just like your bus
tour of New York City

01:17:26.920 --> 01:17:29.230
did not give you a sense
of what New York really

01:17:29.230 --> 01:17:31.840
is, your particular
experience through Harvard

01:17:31.840 --> 01:17:35.200
will be shaded by the one
path you take through here.

01:17:35.200 --> 01:17:38.800
But that path can be much
more windy and multifaceted

01:17:38.800 --> 01:17:41.822
than I think it appears
to us from the outside.

01:17:41.822 --> 01:17:43.030
Last thing I'm going to say--

01:17:45.610 --> 01:17:50.614
I think all of my colleagues
before me suggested to you--

01:17:50.614 --> 01:17:52.280
they gave you the
advice to seek advice.

01:17:52.280 --> 01:17:53.720
And I think that's really good.

01:17:53.720 --> 01:17:55.850
And I would actually
go one step further,

01:17:55.850 --> 01:17:58.630
which is that you
don't really want

01:17:58.630 --> 01:18:01.600
to seek advice so much as
you want to seek criticism.

01:18:01.600 --> 01:18:03.400
And the distinction
that I make is

01:18:03.400 --> 01:18:08.440
that very few of my
colleagues has ever

01:18:08.440 --> 01:18:13.790
been willing to answer the
question, what could I--

01:18:13.790 --> 01:18:15.820
if I go to them and
say, what kind of advice

01:18:15.820 --> 01:18:19.330
would you give me, unless
you're an economist,

01:18:19.330 --> 01:18:21.538
you tend not to want
to demoralize people.

01:18:21.538 --> 01:18:23.290
[LAUGHTER]

01:18:23.290 --> 01:18:26.060
Or at least think
twice about it.

01:18:26.060 --> 01:18:29.451
So it's been very hard for me
to extract meaningful advice

01:18:29.451 --> 01:18:29.950
from that.

01:18:29.950 --> 01:18:32.500
And I think what
tends to come out

01:18:32.500 --> 01:18:36.100
is the person's own experience
of how he or she navigated

01:18:36.100 --> 01:18:36.809
through academia.

01:18:36.809 --> 01:18:39.016
But as I said before, there
are many different paths.

01:18:39.016 --> 01:18:41.570
And there are many different
paths to getting tenure here.

01:18:41.570 --> 01:18:43.959
No two people's
dossier looks the same.

01:18:43.959 --> 01:18:46.000
And so you should take
that with a grain of salt,

01:18:46.000 --> 01:18:48.150
that this was this
person's successful path

01:18:48.150 --> 01:18:50.770
through to tenure, or
through Harvard, et cetera.

01:18:50.770 --> 01:18:53.320
What I do find more valuable
is to actually give people

01:18:53.320 --> 01:18:55.360
license to criticize
you, and to actually

01:18:55.360 --> 01:18:58.510
put yourself in the way of
criticism as much as you can.

01:18:58.510 --> 01:19:00.790
So the trick that I
use is to really play

01:19:00.790 --> 01:19:03.310
on people's own ego.

01:19:03.310 --> 01:19:05.410
That's why I'm a psychologist.

01:19:05.410 --> 01:19:08.110
And it's to ask people
the question, what

01:19:08.110 --> 01:19:10.630
would you do differently,
what would you

01:19:10.630 --> 01:19:12.460
have done if you were me.

01:19:12.460 --> 01:19:14.830
And very few of my colleagues
are comfortable saying,

01:19:14.830 --> 01:19:16.246
oh, no, you did
it just perfectly.

01:19:16.246 --> 01:19:19.060
I couldn't improve
upon what you did.

01:19:19.060 --> 01:19:22.552
But people need to feel
licensed to say, oh, yeah,

01:19:22.552 --> 01:19:24.010
I would have said
this differently,

01:19:24.010 --> 01:19:26.090
or, I wouldn't have done
that, or whatever it is.

01:19:26.090 --> 01:19:27.910
So I try to do this even now.

01:19:27.910 --> 01:19:29.260
After every meeting I have--

01:19:29.260 --> 01:19:31.176
I will ask Judy at the
end of this, what could

01:19:31.176 --> 01:19:32.440
I have done differently--

01:19:32.440 --> 01:19:35.680
every talk that I give,
both within my department

01:19:35.680 --> 01:19:38.610
and also if I have close
friends outside the department.

01:19:38.610 --> 01:19:41.050
So I would just encourage
you to try to put yourself

01:19:41.050 --> 01:19:44.050
in the way of criticism as much
as possible with this growth

01:19:44.050 --> 01:19:48.280
mindset at the
back of your head.

01:19:48.280 --> 01:19:51.010
It's almost certain that you
are not an expert, or not

01:19:51.010 --> 01:19:54.520
perfect at various
aspects of this job.

01:19:54.520 --> 01:19:56.860
And so I think about,
if you were launching

01:19:56.860 --> 01:20:00.260
a satellite to a distant planet,
you've got a couple of choices.

01:20:00.260 --> 01:20:03.820
One is to get the trajectory
just right at the onset, which

01:20:03.820 --> 01:20:06.050
is really hard--
impossible-- or to build

01:20:06.050 --> 01:20:07.510
in a system that
